Amycus' involvement in this battle is recognized in the "Metamorphoses", written by the Roman poet Ovid. Driven with anger due to the death of the loved centaur Eurytus, Amycus smashed the head of innocent Lapith Celadon with a candlestick. Pelates from Pella clubbed him to death using a leg from a maple table, sending Amycus down to the underworld Tartarus.
